question:
In the figure shown, a perpendicular segment is drawn from B in rectangle ABCD to meet diagonal AC at point X.  Side AB is 6 cm and diagonal AC is 10 cm.  How many centimeters away is point X from the midpoint M of the diagonal AC?  Express your answer as a decimal to the nearest tenth.

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(25,0)--(25,15)--(0,15)--cycle,linewidth(1));
draw((0,0)--(25,15),linewidth(1));
draw((7.2,4.3)--(0,15),linewidth(1));
dot((12.5,7.5));
label("$M$",(12.5,7.5),N);
label("$A$",(0,0),S);
label("$B$",(0,15),N);
label("$C$",(25,15),N);
label("$D$",(25,0),S);
label("$X$",(7.2,4.3),SE);
[/asy]

groundtruth:
Because $\triangle PQR$ is isosceles with $PQ=QR$, median $\overline{QM}$ is also an altitude:


[asy]
size(100);
pair P,Q,R,M,NN;
P = (0,0);
Q = (0.5,0.9);
R = (1,0);
NN = (0.5,0);
M = (Q+R)/2;
draw(rightanglemark(Q,NN,P,2.5));
draw(P--Q--R--P);
draw(Q--NN);
label("$P$",P,SW);
label("$R$",R,SE);
label("$Q$",Q,N);
label("$M$",NN,S);
[/asy]

We have $MP = PR/2 = 16$, so right triangle $PQM$ gives us  \begin{align*}
QM &= \sqrt{PQ^2 - PM^2}\\
&= \sqrt{34^2 - 16^2}\\
&= \sqrt{(34-16)(34+16)}\\
& = \boxed{30}.
\end{align*}  (We might also have recognized that $PM/PQ = 8/17$, so $QM/PQ = 15/17$.)

